First, let's find the intersection of sets A and B.

A ∩ B = {x | x ∈ A and x ∈ B}
A ∩ B = {2}

Now, let's find the Cartesian product of A ∩ B and B.

(A ∩ B) × B = {(x, y) | x ∈ A ∩ B and y ∈ B}
(A ∩ B) × B = {(2, 2), (2, 4)}

Now, let's find the Cartesian products of A and B.

A × B = {(x, y) | x ∈ A and y ∈ B}
A × B = {(1, 2), (1, 4), (2, 2), (2, 4), (3, 2), (3, 4)}

Now, let's find the intersection of the Cartesian products of A and B.

(A × B) ∩ ((A ∩ B) × B) = {(x, y) | (x, y) ∈ A × B and (x, y) ∈ (A ∩ B) × B}
(A × B) ∩ ((A ∩ B) × B) = {(2, 2), (2, 4)}

We can see that (A ∩ B) × B = {(2, 2), (2, 4)} and (A × B) ∩ ((A ∩ B) × B) = {(2, 2), (2, 4)}. Therefore, the Cartesian product of A intersection B is equal to the intersection of the Cartesian products of A and B.
